<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="475" pageId="15" pageNumber="474" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1723,2038]" lastBlockId="16.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="475" pageId="15" pageNumber="474">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,461,1903,1929]" pageId="15" pageNumber="474">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among Central American species, recognized by the combination of moderate size (ca. 3.00 mm), the densely punctate pronotum with the reliefs slightly less punctate than the depressions, and the male genitalia. This species has a generalized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1817" box="[598,720,1975,2001]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[598,720,1975,2001]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="474">Hydrochus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
habitus; reliable determinations will require dissection of males. The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[395,518,2011,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="directus">
<emphasis box="[395,518,2011,2037]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="474">H. directus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very slender, therefore superficially somewhat similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Perkins, 2021" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2021" box="[1265,1436,2012,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="474" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aeruginosus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1265,1436,2012,2037]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="474">H. aeruginosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,214,151,177]" pageId="16" pageNumber="475">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,214,151,177]" pageId="16" pageNumber="475" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
; however, details of the two distinctly differ, including shape and size of the parameres, size and shape of the basal piece, and form of the adbl. The habitus of the two species also distinctively differ.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
